#Approach:

💡 IDEA
- Queue me removal FRONT se hota hai.
- Lekin Stack sirf TOP se remove kar sakta hai.
- Isliye recursion se stack ke bottom tak jaate hain.
- Bottom element hi queue ka FRONT hota hai.
- Bottom remove karke baaki elements wapas same order me push kar dete hain.

⚙️ APPROACH
Push(x):
1. Direct stack me push kar do.

Pop():
1. Agar stack empty hai → return -1.
2. Agar stack me sirf 1 element hai:
   - Yehi queue ka front hai.
   - Isko pop karke return kar do.
3. Top element nikaalo.
4. Recursively Pop() call karo.
5. Wapas aate waqt removed top ko stack me push kar do.
6. Recursive call ka answer return kar do.

📝 EXAMPLE

Push(5)
Push(10)
Push(15)

Stack:
Top
15
10
5

Pop()

Step 1:
remove 15

Stack:
10
5

Step 2:
remove 10

Stack:
5

Step 3:
size == 1
return 5

Backtracking:

push(10)
push(15)

Stack becomes:

Top
15
10

Returned Answer = 5

Queue after pop = [10,15]

❓ WHY RECURSION
- Queue ka front stack ke bottom par hota hai.
- Direct bottom access possible nahi hai.
- Recursion temporarily upper elements ko hata deta hai.
- Bottom milne ke baad remaining elements restore kar deta hai.

⏱️ COMPLEXITY
Push : O(1)

Pop  : O(N)
       (Bottom tak jana padta hai)

Space: O(N)
       (Recursive call stack)

🎯 INTERVIEW POINT
- Push cheap, Pop expensive approach.
- Bottom-most stack element = Queue Front.
- Recursion stack ko temporary helper stack ki tarah use kar rahi hai.
- Backtracking ke time elements same order me restore hote hain.
- Isliye queue order maintain rehta hai using only one stack.

#Code:

import java.util.Stack;

class MyQueue {
    Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

    void Push(int x) {
      //You can code here
      stack.push(x);
      return;
    }

    int Pop() {
      //You can code here

      if(stack.isEmpty()) return -1;

      //Base case
      if(stack.size() == 1){
        return stack.pop();
      }

      int top = stack.pop();
      int ans = Pop();
      stack.push(top);

      return ans;
    }
}
